{
  "doc_id": "714",
  "text": "Soybeans are an important crop throughout the world because of their high plant protein and oil content [CITATION_1] . Growing a combination of different crops and species in one field can boost yield and suppress crop diseases [CITATION_2] 6] . Maize/soybean intercropping is a common combination used in some countries to address issues of limited arable land and increasing food demand [6] . In the maize/soybean intercropping system, maize is susceptible to infection by Bipolaris maydis, whereas soybeans present no detectable symptoms of disease [CITATION_3] . B. maydis does not have a soybean pathogen phenotype, nor is it related to any known soybean pathogens. In addition, it does not infect soybeans via touch interactions. A previous microscopy analysis of infected soybeans showed that successful callose deposition and hydrogen peroxide (H 2 O 2 ) production (S1 Fig) may be the first line of defense against B. maydis growth [CITATION_4] . Based on these findings, we hypothesized that soybean resistance to B. maydis is established via NHR, which is the most robust and durable forms of plant resistance in nature. It allows soybean plants to protect themselves against a wide variety of parasitic microorganisms [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
